[
  {
    "lesson_id": "032",
    "trigger_word": "nepo",
    "title": "LESSON 32: THE '-ID-' SUFFIX",
    "header_color": "green",
    "pages": [
      {
        "page": 1,
        "total_pages": 1,
        "content": [
          "The suffix -ID- means \"offspring\" or \"young",
          "of.\" It creates words for children of",
          "animals, people, or descendants.",
          "",
          "ANIMAL OFFSPRING:",
          "hundo   → hundido     = dog → puppy",
          "kato    → katido      = cat → kitten",
          "bovo    → bovido      = cow → calf",
          "ĉevalo  → ĉevalido    = horse → foal",
          "birdo   → birdido     = bird → chick",
          "",
          "HUMAN DESCENDANTS:",
          "reĝo    → reĝido      = king → prince",
          "",
          "IN USE:",
          "La hundido ludas kun sia patrino.",
          "(The puppy plays with its mother.)",
          "-ID- turns any creature into its baby!"
        ],
        "pronunciation": "Leciono tridek du"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "lesson_id": "033",
    "trigger_word": "nombro",
    "title": "LESSON 33: THE '-OBL-' SUFFIX",
    "header_color": "green",
    "pages": [
      {
        "page": 1,
        "total_pages": 1,
        "content": [
          "The suffix -OBL- creates multiples from",
          "numbers. It means \"times\" or \"fold.\"",
          "",
          "MULTIPLES:",
          "du      → duobla    = two → double/twofold",
          "tri     → triobla   = three → triple/threefold",
          "kvar    → kvarobla  = four → quadruple",
          "kvin    → kvinobla  = five → fivefold",
          "dek     → dekobla   = ten → tenfold",
          "",
          "AS VERBS:",
          "duobligi = to double",
          "triobligi = to triple",
          "",
          "IN USE:",
          "La prezo estas duobla nun.",
          "(The price is double now.)",
          "-OBL- multiplies by the number!"
        ],
        "pronunciation": "Leciono tridek tri"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "lesson_id": "034",
    "trigger_word": "sugesti",
    "title": "LESSON 34: THE 'BO-' PREFIX",
    "header_color": "green",
    "pages": [
      {
        "page": 1,
        "total_pages": 1,
        "content": [
          "The prefix BO- indicates relationship by",
          "marriage (in-laws).",
          "",
          "IN-LAW FAMILY:",
          "patro   → bopatro     = father-in-law",
          "patrino → bopatrino   = mother-in-law",
          "frato   → bofrato     = brother-in-law",
          "fratino → bofratino   = sister-in-law",
          "filo    → bofilo      = son-in-law",
          "filino  → bofilino    = daughter-in-law",
          "",
          "REMEMBER:",
          "ge- = both genders (gepatroj = parents)",
          "bo- = by marriage (bogepatroj = in-laws)",
          "",
          "IN USE:",
          "Mia bopatro estas tre afabla.",
          "(My father-in-law is very kind.)"
        ],
        "pronunciation": "Leciono tridek kvar"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "lesson_id": "035",
    "trigger_word": "ekzemplo",
    "title": "LESSON 35: THE '-ER-' SUFFIX",
    "header_color": "green",
    "pages": [
      {
        "page": 1,
        "total_pages": 1,
        "content": [
          "The suffix -ER- means \"unit\" or \"particle.\"",
          "It creates words for single elements of",
          "something that comes in quantities.",
          "",
          "PARTICLES/DROPS:",
          "akvo    → akvero    = water → a drop of water",
          "sablo   → sablero   = sand → a grain of sand",
          "neĝo    → neĝero    = snow → a snowflake",
          "fajro   → fajrero   = fire → a spark",
          "",
          "SINGLE UNITS:",
          "mono    → monero    = money → a coin",
          "pano    → panero    = bread → a crumb",
          "",
          "IN USE:",
          "Akvero falis sur mian nazon.",
          "(A drop of water fell on my nose.)",
          "-ER- picks out one tiny piece from a mass!"
        ],
        "pronunciation": "Leciono tridek kvin"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "lesson_id": "036",
    "trigger_word": "distro",
    "title": "LESSON 36: THE 'DIS-' PREFIX",
    "header_color": "green",
    "pages": [
      {
        "page": 1,
        "total_pages": 1,
        "content": [
          "The prefix DIS- means \"apart,\" \"in different",
          "directions,\" or \"scattered.\" It indicates",
          "separation or dispersal.",
          "",
          "SCATTERING/SEPARATION:",
          "doni    → disdoni   = give → distribute",
          "ĵeti    → disĵeti   = throw → scatter",
          "iri     → disiri    = go → part ways",
          "fali    → disfali   = fall → fall apart",
          "",
          "BREAKING APART:",
          "rompi   → disrompi  = break → shatter",
          "ŝiri    → disŝiri   = tear → to shreds",
          "",
          "IN USE:",
          "Ili diskutis la problemon.",
          "(They discussed the problem.)",
          "DIS- spreads things in all directions!"
        ],
        "pronunciation": "Leciono tridek ses"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "lesson_id": "037",
    "trigger_word": "duono",
    "title": "LESSON 37: THE '-ON-' SUFFIX",
    "header_color": "green",
    "pages": [
      {
        "page": 1,
        "total_pages": 1,
        "content": [
          "The suffix -ON- creates fractions from",
          "numbers. It divides by the number.",
          "",
          "FRACTIONS:",
          "du      → duono       = two → half (1/2)",
          "tri     → triono      = three → third (1/3)",
          "kvar    → kvarono     = four → quarter (1/4)",
          "kvin    → kvinono     = five → fifth (1/5)",
          "dek     → dekono      = ten → tenth (1/10)",
          "",
          "IN USE:",
          "Mi manĝis duonon de la kuko.",
          "(I ate half of the cake.)",
          "",
          "COMPARE -OBL- AND -ON-:",
          "duobla = double (×2)",
          "duono  = half (÷2)",
          "Opposites that work together!"
        ],
        "pronunciation": "Leciono tridek sep"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "lesson_id": "038",
    "trigger_word": "ke",
    "title": "LESSON 38: 'KE' CLAUSES",
    "header_color": "green",
    "pages": [
      {
        "page": 1,
        "total_pages": 1,
        "content": [
          "KE translates to 'that' in English, at the",
          "start of a new clause. Like in German, the new",
          "clause in Esperanto is preceded by a comma.",
          "",
          "BASIC PATTERN:",
          "Mi kredas, ke li venos.",
          "(I believe that he will come.)",
          "",
          "Mi scias, ke vi pravas.",
          "(I know that you are right.)",
          "",
          "COMMON VERBS WITH KE:",
          "pensi ke   = to think that",
          "diri ke    = to say that",
          "esperi ke  = to hope that",
          "",
          "The comma before 'ke' is standard in",
          "Esperanto writing."
        ],
        "pronunciation": "Leciono tridek ok"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "lesson_id": "039",
    "trigger_word": "rideto",
    "title": "LESSON 39: THE '-ET-' SUFFIX",
    "header_color": "green",
    "pages": [
      {
        "page": 1,
        "total_pages": 1,
        "content": [
          "The suffix -ET- is the diminutive suffix in",
          "Esperanto. It makes things smaller, softer,",
          "or gentler. Add -ET- to any root to create",
          "a miniature or mild version of the original.",
          "",
          "MAKING THINGS SMALL:",
          "domo    → dometo     = house → cottage",
          "ridi    → rideti     = laugh → smile",
          "birdo   → birdeto    = bird → little bird",
          "",
          "SOFTENING MEANINGS:",
          "varma   → varmeta    = warm → lukewarm",
          "dormi   → dormeti    = sleep → nap",
          "",
          "rideto = a smile (small laugh)",
          "",
          "-ET- adds a gentle, diminutive quality!"
        ],
        "pronunciation": "Leciono tridek naŭ"
      }
    ]
  }
]
